# R3F Conventions

## Never allocate in the render loop

`useFrame` runs ~60×/sec. Allocating objects there causes GC churn. Hoist them
into `useRef` (or module scope) and mutate in place. This is enforced by the
`@react-three/no-new-in-loop` ESLint rule.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
useFrame(() => {
  const v = new THREE.Vector3(0, 1, 0); // new alloc every frame
  mesh.current.position.lerp(v, 0.1);
});

// ✅ GOOD
const v = useRef(new THREE.Vector3(0, 1, 0));
useFrame(() => {
  mesh.current.position.lerp(v.current, 0.1);
});
```

## Other conventions

- Guard ref access: `if (!ref.current) return;` at the top of `useFrame`.
- Low-poly look: use `flatShading` and low geometry segment counts.
- Animate materials/lights via refs in `useFrame`; don't trigger React re-renders.
- Drive shared animation phases from `src/config/intro.ts` so loader, camera,
  hero gate, and creature stay in sync.
- One station's props per file in `src/scene/props/`; compose reusable meshes from
  `src/scene/components/` (see `low-poly-components` rule).
